Q2: Simulating the Central Limit Theorem

Intent: This question is a simple coding exercise to demonstrate familiarity with how to do basic coding in R.

Load in the generate_data function using the following code (all one line).

source("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/linnykos/561_s2025_public/main/HW1_files/generate_data.R")

This code sources the generate_data function into your current R workspace.

Question 2A: Read the function (either at the URL provided or by typing generate_data into your console), and in one to three sentences, describe the input and output of the provided function and what the function is doing. You may use equations if needed.
Input: Supposed to be an integer > 0
Output: A vector that is a mix of numbers sampled from a normal, a gamma, and a chi-squared distribution
The function first checks that n is a positive integer. It then randomly samples n indices from the set {1, 2, 3}. Each sampled index determines which distribution to draw from:
If the index is 1, the value is sampled from a Normal distribution: \(X \sim \mathcal{N}(10, 1)\). If the index is 2, the value is sampled from a Gamma distribution: \(X \sim \text{Gamma}(2, 2)\). If the index is 3, the value is sampled from a Chi-squared distribution: \(X \sim \chi^2(3)\)

Question 2B: We will now be using the generate_data function. Observe that if we run the following code, we would compute a (random, empirical) mean of the a dataset with n=10 samples:

set.seed(1)
mean(generate_data(n=10))
#> [1] 5.199818

Repeat the above code 10,000 times (i.e., 10,000 trials, but keeping n=10 for each trial), and plot a histogram of the 10,000 different empirical means with 100 breaks (i.e., breaks = 100). Repeat this process for n with values of 1, 2, 3, 5, and 100, and plot these six histograms in order of increasing n.

Figure 1 shows the desired plot you aim to reproduce. In particular, reproduce the X- and Y-labels, the title of the plot, and the plot layout. (Hint: You might find the par function useful, especially the mar and mfrow arguments, as well as the paste function. See the documentation for par.)

Figure 1: The figure you are trying to reproduce (without the Sample watermark) in Question 2B, barring the dimensions/proportions of the figure itself and randomness inherent to the simulation. 

library(tidyverse)
#>  Attaching core tidyverse packages  tidyverse 2.0.0 
#>  dplyr     1.1.4      readr     2.1.4
#>  forcats   1.0.0      stringr   1.5.0
#>  ggplot2   3.5.1      tibble    3.2.1
#>  lubridate 1.9.2      tidyr     1.3.0
#>  purrr     1.0.2     
#>  Conflicts  tidyverse_conflicts() 
#>  dplyr::filter() masks stats::filter()
#>  dplyr::lag()    masks stats::lag()
#>  Use the conflicted package (<http://conflicted.r-lib.org/>) to force all conflicts to become errors
library(patchwork)
means_df = tibble()

for (n in c(1,2,3,5,10,100)) {
  set.seed(1)
  means = c()
  for (i in seq(1, 10000)) {
    mean_curr = mean(generate_data(n=n))
    means = append(means, mean_curr)
  }
  means_n <- tibble(n = n, mean = means)
  means_df <- bind_rows(means_df, means_n)
}

ggplot(means_df) +
  geom_histogram(aes(x=mean)) +
  xlab("Value") +
  facet_wrap(~ n, 
             scales = "free", 
             labeller = as_labeller(function(n) paste("Sample size:", n))) +
  theme_bw() +
  ylab("Frquency")
#> `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

Question 2C: In one to three sentences, write how the plot you reproduced helps to verify the Central Limit Theorem.
We have a mix of multiple random variables from three different distributions. As the sample size increases, the distribution of the mean of the sampled data points from these distributions approaches a normal distribution, as the CLT states.

Here are brief descriptions of each variable:

  • Donor.ID: The anonymized ID of the donor who donated their brain to AD research
  • Age.at.Death: The age of the donor when they passed away
  • Sex: The biological sex of the donor. (Kevins comment: In this study, it seems like this is strictly only Male or Female?)
  • APOE4.Status: Y (for yes) or N (for no) if the donor has a particular genetic variant that is known to be a risk factor for AD
  • Cognitive.Status: Whether the donor has dementia or not based on a wide array of cognitive assessments before death
  • Last.CASI.Score: The last score the donor had, measured via CASI (a specific set of cognitive questions), before death
  • Braak: Different severities of neuropathology based on the donors brain tissue, extracted after the donors consent and death

Hopefully, this is a reminder to carefully describe your study variables in any dataset you publish or collaborate on!

Question 3A: Describe, in two to four sentences, what the head(df) and summary(df) results display.
The head function displays the first 6 observations from the dataframe. The summary function, for numerical variables, displays certain useful statistics like Min, Median, Mean, etc For other variables, it displays the length, class (high level type), and mode (low level type).

Question 3C: Youll note that in summary(df), the variable Age.at.Death is a character, even though it should be a numeric. This is because there are values of 90+. As a simple diagnostic, 1) replace all the 90+ values in df$Age.at.Death with 90, 2) convert df$Age.at.Death from a character to a numeric, and 3) plot a histogram of df$Age.at.Death.

Figure 2 shows the desired plot you aim to reproduce.

Figure 2: The figure you are trying to reproduce (without the Sample watermark) in Question 3C, barring the dimensions/proportions of the figure itself. 

df <- df %>%
  mutate(
    Age.at.Death = as.numeric(case_when(
      Age.at.Death == "90+" ~ "90",
      TRUE ~ Age.at.Death  # keep as-is if no match
    )
    )
  )

ggplot(df) +
  geom_histogram(aes(x=Age.at.Death), binwidth = 5, boundary = 65) +
  xlab("Donor age") +
  theme_bw() +
  ylab("Frquency") +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = seq(65, 90, by = 5)) + 
  scale_y_continuous(breaks = seq(0, 60, by = 10),
                     limits = c(0, 60))

Question 3G: This question will be slightly challenging. The table() function is not as useful when there are many unique values (such as in Last.CASI.Score). To overcome this, look up the documentation for the cut and quantile functions. The goal is to use the table(), cut(), and quantile() to show the relation of the quantiles of Last.CASI.Score with Cognitive.Status. You will want to use na.rm=TRUE when using the quantile() function.

Figure 4 shows the desired output you aim to reproduce.

Figure 4: The intended output of Question 3G. 

quantiles = df %>% pull(Last.CASI.Score) %>% quantile(na.rm=T)
df = df %>% mutate(Last.CASI.Score = cut(Last.CASI.Score, quantiles))
table(df$Last.CASI.Score, df$Cognitive.Status)
#>          
#>           Dementia No dementia
#>   (66,80]       16           1
#>   (80,89]       10           8
#>   (89,95]        2          15
#>   (95,99]        3          13

In one to two sentences, describe what you can learn from the relation between Last.CASI.Score and Cognitive.Status based on this result.
Based on this, it seems like people with dementia tend to have lower CASI scores, while those without dementia tend to have higher CASI scores.
